ternational meetings 
In addition, it is planned that the central ideas will be presented to a more general lay audience, potentially by means of the annual Royal Society Summer School.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:technicalSummary>The field of binaural hearing is undergoing something of a revolution, with a number of recent studies questioning long-standing views of how sensitivity to binaural cues is generated at the level of individual neurones, as well as the form of any neural code underpinning behavioural sensitivity to these cues. The programme of work proposed will examine neural mechanisms of binaural hearing in experimental animals and human listeners, incorporating emerging principles of mammalian binaural hearing into a physiologically plausible model. Specific experiments will examine the neural basis of sensitivity to ITDs in low- and high-frequency sounds using single-neurone recordings from the auditory brainstem and midbrain of experimental animals, iontophoresis of neurotransmitters and their antagonists in vivo, 2-photon imaging and intracellular recording techniques in brainstem slices, human psychophysics, functional imaging and and neural modeling. The aim is to provide for a model of binaural hearing from the level of single neurones to human psychophysical performance. These investigations will further our understanding of the neural mechanisms that contribute to the processing of binaural sounds in the brain, and will lead to the development of models of hearing that ultimately will increase our understanding of human brain function and dysfunction.</gtr:technicalSummary><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2009-09-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/organisation/C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C"><gtr:id>C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2004-10-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>803188</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collabo